<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="348" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1465,1598]" pageId="1" pageNumber="348">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1465,1490]" pageId="1" pageNumber="348">Remarks.</emphasis>
The narrow forewing of 
<taxonomicName box="[614,728,1466,1489]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Pityocona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="348" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[614,728,1466,1489]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="348">Pityocona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with several distinct black spots and the male genitalia with bifurcate uncus make 
<taxonomicName box="[399,513,1502,1525]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Pityocona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="348" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[399,513,1502,1525]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="348">Pityocona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
distinguishable from its most closely related genera. The diagnostic characters of this genus include the bifurcate uncus, the valva curved approximately beyond middle and extending inward distally, and the extremely narrow vinculum in the male genitalia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
